     <p><strong><p><strong>Carlos Alberto Sánchez, <em>Blooming in the Ruins: How Mexican Philosophy Can Guide Us toward the Good Life</em>, Oxford University Press, 2024, 328pp., $19.99 (hbk), ISBN 9780197691007.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by José Jorge Mendoza, University of Washington</strong></p>
     <p>There are few introductions to Latin American philosophy and even fewer devoted specifically to Mexican philosophy. Carlos Alberto Sánchez’s <em>Blooming in the Ruins: How Mexican Philosophy Can Guide Us toward the Good Life</em> not only introduces the reader to key concepts, figures, themes, and texts in Mexican philosophy, but, by drawing on personal narratives, also makes a convincing case for how Mexican philosophy can be put to use in one’s life, even if one is not Mexican. After all, as Sánchez puts it: “we are not all ancient Greeks, and yet we find it very ordinary to take up the ideas of ancient Greek philosophers and seek to live by them” (272).</p> <p>The book is broken down into five parts, totaling twenty-eight (short) chapters in...
